diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Disorders
diagnoses.description: Conditions where the immune system mistakenly attacks the body, potentially causing varied symptoms such as hearing loss, miscarriage, and systemic reactions.

diagnoses.name: Neurological Disorders
diagnoses.description: Issues affecting the nervous system that can lead to symptoms like blepharospasm and irritability.

diagnoses.name: Stress and Anxiety
diagnoses.description: Psychological conditions that can contribute to irritability, miscarriage, and exacerbate Kounis syndrome.

diagnoses.name: Hormonal Imbalances
diagnoses.description: Discrepancies in hormone levels that can result in miscarriage, irritability, and potentially influence the severity of Kounis syndrome.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Diseases
diagnoses.description: Infections can lead to hearing loss (either directly or through treatment), miscarriage, and systemic inflammatory responses.

diagnoses.name: Allergic Reactions
diagnoses.description: Severe allergies can trigger Kounis syndrome, a type of allergic acute coronary syndrome, and potentially cause systemic reactions affecting various body systems.

diagnoses.name: Toxic Exposures
diagnoses.description: Exposure to certain toxins can lead to hearing loss, miscarriage, and other systemic effects.

diagnoses.name: Vascular Disorders
diagnoses.description: Conditions affecting the blood vessels, which could predispose individuals to Kounis syndrome and cause complications in pregnancy.

diagnoses.name: Genetic Conditions
diagnoses.description: Genetic abnormalities can result in a wide range of symptoms including hearing loss and can influence the risk of miscarriage.

diagnoses.name: Metabolic Disorders
diagnoses.description: Imbalances in the body's metabolism can lead to symptoms like irritability, and impact overall health possibly affecting pregnancy outcomes.

diagnoses.name: Anaphylaxis
diagnoses.description: A severe, life-threatening allergic reaction that can occur suddenly and affect the whole body.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A rare genetic condition characterized by sudden and recurrent episodes of swelling in various parts of the body, including the abdomen, face, limbs, and airway.

diagnoses.name: Acute Urinary Retention
diagnoses.description: A sudden inability to urinate causing painful bladder distention and related symptoms; can be associated with autonomic dysreflexia in some cases.

diagnoses.name: Acute Intestinal Obstruction
diagnoses.description: Blockage of the intestine that prevents the passage of contents. Can cause abdominal cramps, vomiting, and inability to pass stool or gas.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Idiopathic Urticaria
diagnoses.description: A condition where hives or welts appear on the skin without a known cause, potentially accompanied by angioedema.

diagnoses.name: Mast Cell Activation Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A condition caused by inappropriate release of mast cell mediators, leading to symptoms such as hives, angioedema, abdominal cramps, and anaphylactoid reactions.

diagnoses.name: Food Allergy
diagnoses.description: An adverse health effect arising from a specific immune response that occurs reproducibly on exposure to a given food, often causing hives, angioedema, and gastrointestinal symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Drug Allergy
diagnoses.description: Immunologically mediated adverse reactions to medications, which may present with hives, angioedema, respiratory distress, and gastrointestinal symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Acute Pancreatitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the pancreas that causes severe abdominal pain and may be associated with systemic inflammatory responses.

diagnoses.name: Toxic Shock Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, life-threatening complication of certain bacterial infections, characterized by sudden onset of fever, rash, hypotension, and multiorgan involvement.

diagnoses.description: A neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms. It's frequently characterized by intense, debilitating headaches. Symptoms may include nausea, vomiting, difficulty speaking, numbness or tingling, and sensitivity to light and sound.
The most common type of headache. Symptoms include dull, aching head pain and tightness or pressure across the forehead or on the sides and back of the head.
Painful attacks of headaches on one side of the head. It may be accompanied by tearing, nasal congestion, and restlessness.

Often called a 'mini stroke', a TIA has symptoms that mirror those of a stroke, including headaches, weakness, and difficulty speaking, but typically lasts only a few minutes and causes no permanent damage.
A medical condition in which poor blood flow to the brain results in cell death. Symptoms can include headache, weakness, confusion, and problems seeing.

A chronic, typically progressive disease involving damage to the sheaths of nerve cells in the brain and spinal cord. Symptoms may include numbness, impairment of speech and of muscular coordination, blurred vision, and severe fatigue.
A mass or growth of abnormal cells in the brain. Symptoms may include headaches, weakness, balance and walking problems, and seizures.
An inflammation of the membranes (meninges) surrounding your brain and spinal cord. The swelling from meningitis typically triggers symptoms such as headache, fever, and a stiff neck.
A type of migraine that primarily affects balance and can cause vertigo, sometimes without the usual migraine headache. Additional symptoms can include sensitivity to motion, light, and sound.
A condition caused by a very low level of blood sugar (glucose), your body's main energy source. Weakness and headaches are common symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease characterized by inflammation of various parts of the body. It can manifest with skin, joint, renal, nervous system involvement, including nonscarring alopecia, hemolytic anemia, myelitis, oral ulcers, and mononeuritis multiplex.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory disorder affecting many joints, including those in the hands and feet. In severe cases, it can affect other tissues throughout the body and cause problems such as rheumatoid nodules and vasculitis that can lead to similar symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that attacks the glands that provide lubrication to the eyes and mouth. It can also affect other parts of the body, including nerves and blood cells, potentially leading to hemolytic anemia and mononeuritis multiplex.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.description: This condition shares characteristics with diseases like SLE, scleroderma, and polymyositis. Symptoms can include those listed, as part of a wider range of autoimmune responses.

diagnoses.name: Polyarteritis Nodosa
diagnoses.description: A serious blood vessel disease where small and medium-sized arteries become swollen and damaged. It can lead to symptoms like mononeuritis multiplex and skin ulcers.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout the body. Symptoms may include oral ulcers, skin problems, and potentially, neurological complications.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease marked by muscle weakness and skin rash. While not as commonly associated with the full symptom list, it could potentially explain some of the manifestations.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the blood vessels that can cause a wide array of symptoms, depending on which organs are affected. Specific variants like microscopic polyangiitis could lead to symptoms like hemolytic anemia and mononeuritis multiplex.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: A tick-borne illness that can cause a variety of symptoms, sometimes including neurological manifestations such as mononeuritis multiplex, depending on the stage of the disease.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: Human immunodeficiency virus/acquired immune deficiency syndrome can lead to a wide range of symptoms and opportunistic infections that could potentially cause or mimic the listed symptoms.
